Trade offs + Considerations

A running log of design decisions that cannot be recovered from the code alone.
Write entries as you go; future agents and humans read this to understand *why*.

Format per entry:
  == Topic ==
  - Short bullet points. What was considered, what was picked, what was left out.
  - Include the reason a rejected option was rejected (not just "we chose X").


== Governance layer ==

- Picked a filesystem-based governance layer (docs + log.json + SCRATCHPAD.md) over a
  tool-enforced one (e.g. a linter plugin or MCP server) because Opus 4.7 is explicitly
  trained to read/write files across turns. A separate enforcement service adds moving
  parts; docs in the repo are version-controlled and human-reviewable.
- SPARC task states (spec → pseudocode → architecture → refinement → done) were picked
  over simpler todo/doing/done because the adversarial-refinement gate is load-bearing —
  collapsing it into "doing" hides whether a task has been challenged.


== Model assignments ==

- Orchestrator at Opus 4.7, implementer at Sonnet 4.6. The cost ratio justifies the
  split: orchestrator decisions are rare and high-value; implementer calls are many and
  cheap. A single-model setup would either overspend or underperform on planning.
- Adversary explicitly at the *same* tier as the implementer. A weaker adversary
  rubber-stamps. A stronger adversary finds issues the implementer had no path to
  surface in the first place — unfair and noisy.


== What was NOT adopted ==

- No telemetry export to an external tracing service. log.json is enough for the
  current scale; adding OpenTelemetry would be premature.
- No automated CI enforcement of "no write without passing adversarial_check".
  Planned, but not built — governance rules are currently honor-system + review.
